<%!-- About section --%>
<section id="about" class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-20 lg:px-8">
  <div class="text-center mb-12">
    <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-green-700 dark:text-green-400 mb-3">
      Meet Your Guide
    </p>
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">About Dr. Shelley Ball</h2>
  </div>

  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <div class="prose prose-lg mx-auto text-base-content leading-8">
      <p class="text-xl font-medium text-base-content/80 mb-6">
        Biologist. Educator. Storyteller. Advocate for the natural world.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-6">
        Dr. Shelley Ball has spent a career building bridges between people and the
        natural world. As the founder of Biosphere Environmental Education, her mission
        is simple and enduring: to connect people to nature, and to inspire them to
        care about it and protect it.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-6">
        Shelley holds a Ph.D. in Biology with a specialization in evolutionary ecology
        and population genetics, and was among the pioneers of DNA Barcoding — a
        DNA-based tool now used globally to inventory the diversity of life on Earth.
        With nearly 30 years of teaching experience spanning kindergarten through
        graduate school, she brings rare breadth to every educational encounter.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-6">
        Her work extends well beyond the laboratory and classroom. Shelley is a <strong>Fellow of the Royal Canadian Geographical Society</strong>, a
        <strong>TEDx Speaker</strong>
        (Ottawa), and a professional public speaker and
        author. In December 2016, she was a member of the inaugural <strong>Homeward Bound Women in Science Leadership Expedition to Antarctica</strong>.
        In March 2018, she represented the Canadian Federation of University Women
        (CFUW) at the <strong>United Nations 62nd Commission on the Status of Women</strong>,
        and was honoured with the <strong>2018 CFUW National Mentoring Award</strong>
        — recognition of her longstanding dedication to mentoring women in science and
        academia.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-6">
        Shelley currently serves as Chair of the Environment Committee for
        CFUW – Perth &amp; District, and as a mentor with the CFUW National Mentoring
        Program. She is also a career mentor and life coach, helping individuals
        discover and pursue their true vocations.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-8">
        Whether she is guiding an expedition through a wilderness landscape, speaking
        on a conference stage, or crouching in a meadow to identify a wildflower,
        Shelley brings the same infectious passion: a deep love of nature and an
        unwavering belief that understanding it is the first step toward protecting it.
      </p>
    </div>

